\subsection{Repetition coding to correct phase errors}

Of course, there is nothing special about $\sigma_{x}$ and the standard basis $|0\rangle /|1\rangle$. We could just rotate the entire error correction scheme so that it protects against $\sigma_{z}$ errors, or any errors along any axis. In particular, to correct single $\sigma_{z}$ errors, we just make use of the repetition code in the $| \pm\rangle=|0\rangle \pm|1\rangle$ basis (ignoring normalization). Now a state $|\psi\rangle=\alpha|+\rangle+\beta|-\rangle$ is encoded as $|\widehat{\psi}\rangle=\alpha|+++\rangle+\beta \mid-$ $--\rangle$. The syndrome measurement projectors become $\Pi=\mathbb{1}_{1} \otimes(|++\rangle\langle++|+|--\rangle\langle--|)_{23}$ for $s_{1}=0$ and $\Pi^{\prime}=\mathbb{1}_{1} \otimes(|+-\rangle\langle+-|+|-+\rangle\langle-+|)_{23}$ for $s_{1}=1$, and similarly for $s_{2}$. The decoding lookup table is the same, only now the correction operation is $\sigma_{z}$ on the indicated qubit. In this way the repetition code can correct single phase errors $\sigma_{z}$.

